Title : John Francis Ropek
Text : '''John Francis Ropek''' (January 3, 1917 â€“ November 9, 2009) was an American meteorologist and oceanographer.

==Early life and education==
John Francis Ropek was born in [[Dunmore, Pennsylvania]]. His parents were Josephine and Franciszek Ropek. Ropek was an alumnus of [[Dunmore High School]].<ref>[http://www.legis.state.pa.us/cfdocs/legis/PN/Public/btCheck.cfm?txtType=HTM&sessYr=2011&sessInd=0&billBody=H&billTyp=R&billNbr=0631&pn=3251 John F. Ropek was mentioned among distinguished natives of Dunmore in House Resolution No. 631, Session of 2012, The General Assembly of Pennsylvania.]</ref>  He earned degrees in chemistry and meteorology from [[New York University]].<ref>[http://ww2.somdnews.com/stories/12092009/recobi140632_32201.shtml "Obituary: John F. Ropek, 92, Lusby," ''The Calvert Recorder'' (December 9, 2009)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140426234216/http://ww2.somdnews.com/stories/12092009/recobi140632_32201.shtml |date=April 26, 2014 }}.</ref>

==Career==
During [[World War II]] Ropek was drafted and served in the [[United States Army Air Forces]] in the Pacific, attaining the rank of captain. He became a civilian researcher after the war. In 1957 he was assigned to the [[USS Nautilus (SSN-571)|USS Nautilus]]. As one of 116 men aboard this nuclear submarine, Ropek was involved in pioneering oceanographic studies under the polar ice cap of the [[North Pole]], resulting in the report "Characteristics of Polar Ice Observed During the 1957 Arctic Cruise of the USS Nautilus" (Defense Technical Information Center 1958).<ref>[http://thetimes-tribune.com/news/local-history/dunmore-native-on-historic-voyage-1.1357492 Cheryl A. Kashuba, "Dunmore Native on Historic Voyage," ''Scranton Times-Tribune'' (August 12, 2012)].</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=Ep4ZOAAACAAJ Walter I. Wittmann and John F. Ropek, "Characteristics of Polar Ice Observed During the 1957 Arctic Cruise of the USS Nautilus" (Defense Technical Information Center 1958)].</ref><ref>John Ropek is mentioned as a civilian member of the "Operation Sunshine" expedition in the captain's memoir; [https://books.google.com/books?id=mo20qJNE8x4C&lpg=PT110&ots=sSsiqejnJp&dq=Ropek%20Nautilus&pg=PT110#v=onepage&q=Ropek%20Nautilus&f=false William R. Anderson, ''The Ice Diaries:  The True Story of One of Mankind's Greatest Adventures'' (Thomas Nelson Inc. 2008):  p. 90].</ref>

As a scientist he published many technical papers, such as ''US Navy Hydrographic Office synoptic and prognostic wave charts'' (US Navy Hydrographic Office 1955), and "An Application of Naval Oceanographic Development to Inland Waters" (Defense Technical Information Center 1967).<ref>[https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/bibliography/47416#/summary John J. Schule and John F. Ropek, ''US Navy Hydrographic Office synoptic and prognostic wave charts'' (Washington DC:  US Navy Hydrographic Office 1955)].</ref><ref>John C. Wilkerson and John F. Ropek, "An Application of Naval Oceanographic Development to Inland Waters" (Defense Technical Information Center 1967).</ref>

Later, Ropek was deputy director of the prediction division of the [[Naval Oceanographic Office]].  Late in life he lived in [[Lusby, Maryland]].<ref>[http://ww2.somdnews.com/stories/12092009/recobi140632_32201.shtml "Obituary: John F. Ropek, 92, Lusby," ''The Calvert Recorder'' (December 9, 2009)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140426234216/http://ww2.somdnews.com/stories/12092009/recobi140632_32201.shtml |date=April 26, 2014 }}.</ref>

John F. Ropek died November 9, 2009, at Calvert Memorial Hospital in Maryland. He was 92.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/12/04/AR2009120404247.html Adam Bernstein, "John F. Ropek, Meteorologist, Oceanographer," ''The Washington Post'' (December 5, 2009)].</ref> He is buried in Saint Anthony of Padua Cemetery, [[Dickson City, Pennsylvania]].<ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/58772457 Find A Grave memorial for John F. Robek (1917-2009)].</ref>

